06685nam a22008175i 9781529226072DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815292260727 a10.56687/97815292260722doi  a(DE-B1597)645743  a(OCoLC)1374818920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0420002bisacsh00aChildren's Work in African Agriculture :bThe Harmful and the Harmless /ced. by James Sumberg, Rachel Sabates-Wheeler. 1aBristol : bBristol University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b6 Black and White  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Figures, Tables and Boxes -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes on Contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tForeword -- tChildren's Work in African Agriculture: An Introduction -- tTheorizing 'Harm' in Relation to Children's Work -- tUnderstanding Children's Harmful Work: The Methodological Landscape -- tEducation and Work: Children's Lives in Rural Sub-Saharan Africa -- tDisabled Children and Work -- tValue Chain Governance and Children's Work in Agriculture -- tBlurred Definitions and Imprecise Indicators: Rethinking Social Assistance for Children's Work -- tChildren's Work in Ghana: Policies and Politics -- tChildren's Work in Shallot Production on the Keta Peninsula, South-Eastern Ghana -- tChildren's Work in West African Cocoa Production: Drivers, Contestations and Critical Reflections -- tChildren's Harmful Work in Ghana's Lake Volta Fishery: Beyond Discourses of Child Trafficking -- tChildren's Work in African Agriculture: Ways Forward -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aEPDF and EPUB available Open Access under CC-BY-NC-ND licence. Millions of children throughout Africa undertake many forms of farm and domestic work. Some of this work is for wages, some is on their family's own small plots and some is forced and/or harmful. This book examines children's involvement in such work. It argues that framing all children's engagement in economic activity as 'child labour', with all the associated negative connotations, is problematic. This is particularly the case in Africa where many rural children must work to survive and where, the contributors argue, much of the work undertaken is not harmful. The conceptual and case-based chapters reframe the debate about children's work and harm in rural Africa with the aim of shifting research, public discourse and policy so that they better serve the interest of rural children and their families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh1 aAbubakari, Abdulai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsante, Felix Ankomah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, Inka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellwood-Howard, Imogen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBock, Rosilin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdillon, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunne, Máiréad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgyir, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrimpong Boamah, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphreys, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Vicky, econtribut